 Leading Soviet Health Resort: Reminiscences of the Social History of Jurmala, Latvia -- tChapter 12. From Port to Resort: Art, Heritage and Identity in the Regeneration of Margate0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHistories of seaports and coastal resorts have usually been kept in separate compartments. This book brings them together and looks at how resort development affected historic ports during the rise and development of the seaside holiday in Europe from the 18th century to the 20th, and what the attributes of ports (fishing, harbour crafts, the whiff of the exotic, fishermen’s homes and families) contributed to the attractions of resorts. Case-studies drawn from across Europe, from Wales and the Netherlands to Norway, Latvia and Spain, bring original perspectives to bear on these histories and relationships, and consider their influence on seaside heritage and regeneration at a time when coastal settlements are increasingly using their past to secure their future. The book will interest academics in tourism studies, history, geography and cultural studies, as well as provide essential information and analysis for policy-makers in coastal regeneration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHarborszEuropexHistory. 0aSeaside resortszEuropexHistory. 0aTourismzEuropexHistory. 4aGEOGRAPHY. 4aGeneral & world history. 4aTourism industry. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  aEuropean seaside towns.  acoastal resorts.  ahistoric ports.  aresort development.  aseaports.  aseaside heritage.  aseaside regeneration.1 aBorsay, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorsay, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrodie